<DOC><DOCNO> AP900209-0269 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-02-09-90 1511EST</FILEID><FIRST>u f BC-BoardofTrade Close   02-09 0223</FIRST><SECOND>BC-Board of Trade, Close,0232</SECOND><HEAD>Crop Futures Rise on China Wheat Offer</HEAD><DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   Grain and soybean futures prices closed mostlyhigher Friday on the Chicago Board of Trade, supported by theAgriculture Department's offer to subsidize sales of 1 millionmetric tons of wheat to China.   The USDA announcement, which came after the close of tradingThursday, stirred speculation that subsidized wheat also will beoffered to the Soviet Union, said Susan Leighty, a grain-marketanalyst with Prudential-Bache Securities Inc.   She said rumors of upcoming export bonus offers to both nationshad circulated in the markets in the past month.   Under a program designed to increase export sales of U.S. grain,the USDA provides grain or grain credits to exporters who sellgrain to targeted nations.   The near-month wheat contract, for delivery in March, ralliedmost strongly amid speculation that the Chinese would take someold-crop wheat in addition to new-crop, analysts said.   At the close, wheat futures were \ cent lower to 4{ cents higherwith the contract for delivery in March at $3.87 a bushel; cornfutures were \ cent to } cent higher with March at $2.39} a bushel;oats were { cent to 1\ cents higher with March at $1.38 a bushel;soybeans were 1{ cents to 3 cents higher with March at $5.66} abushel.</TEXT></DOC>